How students from primary schools to junior colleges are scoring for their Mother Tongue

This dataset plots percentage of passes for Mother Tongue language over the years and tagged to ethnic group. The general trend across the years is a decreasing one. While we are still above 95% passes across all levels, the decreasing % trend when superimposed onto the ethnic Malay demographic questions why are more people failing their own Mother Tongue language.

Caveats: - This fails to account for student who dont identify as Malay (e.g.mixed-race students who still take Malay). - This assumes that if you put Malay as your ethnicity, you are taking Malay language for your Mother Tongue. - Note that for PSLE its listed as (A* - C).

pass <- read.csv(file = './pass.csv', header = TRUE)
pass %>% 
  filter(race == 'Malay' & level != "gce-nt") %>%

Its always been a given and easy subject to score as long as you speak it at home or with your grandparents. I mean, its hard to fail Malay if you are are Melayu. Kalau tak belajar pun, masih boleh pass.

Kan?

The most worrying part is the PSLE graph it probably aligns with the desas-desus that younger Malay Singaporeans are getting out of touch with the Malay language.

And that got me thinking, in the entire Malay paper, what are the things that you need to hafal? - Peribahasa definitely. - Penjodoh bilangan, yes. - Kamus Dewan? Kidding, tak perlu.

While peribahasa constitutes only a small component of the Malay paper across all levels, I thought peribahasa is good entry point into visualising something unique to the Malay language.

And maybe just coz its wacky enough for people to get interested in the getting to know this aspect of the Malay language.

Analysing peribahasa list from Wikipedia Malaysia

The following is the results of the exploratory data analysis on peribahasa.

# Import data
peri_csv <- read.csv(file = './peri.csv', header = TRUE)
peri_csv$Peribahasa <- gsub("\\s*\\([^\\)]+\\)", "", as.character(peri_csv$Peribahasa))
peri_csv$Peribahasa <- tolower(peri_csv$Peribahasa)
peri_csv$Makannya <- gsub("\\s*\\([^\\)]+\\)", "", as.character(peri_csv$Makannya))

peri_csv_clean <- peri_csv %>% filter(!str_detect(Peribahasa, '='))
peri_csv_clean$Peribahasa <- str_replace_all(peri_csv_clean$Peribahasa, ':', ',')

peri_csv %>% head()

The dataset is scraped from Wikipedia pages Senarai peribahasa (A-M) and Senarai peribahasa (NZ). Theyve already been tabulated into peribahasa and its corresponding meaning.

Data cleaning the peribahasa removes instances where the author writes some translation between brackets within the peribahasa entries.

After which we execute the following steps to analyse this dataset:

  • Tokenising each peribahasa into its own word
  • Each word is reduced to its root word
  • Removing the stop words like dan from the list of root words
# tokenising malay words
tokenised <- tibble(line = 1:2286, text = peri_csv_clean$Peribahasa) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text)

# cleaning the stop words first, then changing to root words
tokenised %>% 
#  anti_join(malaystopwords, by = c("word" = "stopwords")) %>% 
  group_by(word) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) 
# changing to root words and cleaning away stop words
tokenised_root_clean <- tokenised %>% 
  stem_malay(dictionary = malayrootwords, 
             col_feature1 = "word") %>% 
  anti_join(malaystopwords, by = c("Root Word" = "stopwords"))
## 'Root Word' is now returned instead of 'root_word'
### This means when I change to root words, it increases the number of stopwords and hence they get shaved. 

# bigram for words that coincide together
tibble(line = 1:2286, text = peri_csv_clean$Peribahasa) %>%
  unnest_tokens(ngram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 2) %>% 
  group_by(ngram) %>%
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% head(20)

Using Indonesian dictionary from UDpipe to add parts-of-speech tagging to the list of cleaned tokenised words

indo   <- udpipe::udpipe_download_model(language = "indonesian-gsd")
## Downloading udpipe model from https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jwijffels/udpipe.models.ud.2.5/master/inst/udpipe-ud-2.5-191206/indonesian-gsd-ud-2.5-191206.udpipe to C:/Users/sitia/Desktop/aish-side-projects/_R-stats/Peribahasa/indonesian-gsd-ud-2.5-191206.udpipe

## Downloading finished, model stored at 'C:/Users/sitia/Desktop/aish-side-projects/_R-stats/Peribahasa/indonesian-gsd-ud-2.5-191206.udpipe'
indo_dict <- udpipe_load_model(file = "./indonesian-gsd-ud-2.5-191206.udpipe")

pos_peri <- udpipe::udpipe_annotate(indo_dict, x = peri_csv_clean$Peribahasa) %>%
  as.data.frame()

pos_peri_clean <- pos_peri %>% 
  mutate(id = str_extract(doc_id, "[^doc]+$")) %>% 
  select(id, sentence, token_id, lemma, upos) %>% 
  #anti_join(malaystopwords, by = c("lemma" = "stopwords")) %>%
  filter(upos != 'PUNCT') %>% 
  stem_malay(dictionary = malayrootwords, 
             col_feature1 = "lemma") 
## 'Root Word' is now returned instead of 'root_word'
pos_peri_clean %>% head()

We can also divide the part of speech into nouns, verbs and adj. I think the nouns and verbs will come in handy in the later part.

# nouns
nouns <- pos_peri_clean %>% filter(upos == 'noun') %>% group_by(`Col Word`, `Root Word`) %>% count() %>% arrange(desc(n))
#nouns %>% View()
#write.csv(nouns, 'nouns.csv')

# verb
verbs <- pos_peri_clean %>% filter(upos == 'verb') %>% group_by(`Col Word`, `Root Word`) %>% count() %>% arrange(desc(n))

# adj
adj <- pos_peri_clean %>% filter(upos == 'adj') %>% group_by(`Col Word`, `Root Word`) %>% count() %>% arrange(desc(n))

Trying ti-idf on the makna column

  • Term Frequency: is a scoring of the frequency of the word in the current document.

  • Inverse Document Frequency: is a scoring of how rare the word is across documents.

  • A high weight in tfidf is reached by a high term frequency (in the given document) and a low document frequency of the term in the whole collection of documents; the weights hence tend to filter out common terms.

(ERM,doesnt it mean for a shorter review, the TF is higher and if it so happened they use gibberish that is unique, the IDF will be higher also constituing a high tf_idf value in the end?)

# Doing a TI-IDF on the makna coloumn

words <- tibble(line = 1:2286, text = peri_csv_clean$Makannya) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text) %>%
  count(line, word)

total_words <- words %>% 
  group_by(line) %>% 
  summarize(total = sum(n))

words <- left_join(words, total_words)
## Joining, by = "line"
results <- words %>% bind_tf_idf(word, line, n)

results %>% group_by(line) %>% top_n(2, wt = tf_idf) %>% anti_join(malaystopwords, by = c("word" = "stopwords")) %>% 
  stem_malay(dictionary = malayrootwords, 
             col_feature1 = "word") 
## `mutate_all()` ignored the following grouping variables:
## Column `line`
## Use `mutate_at(df, vars(-group_cols()), myoperation)` to silence the message.
## 'Root Word' is now returned instead of 'root_word'
# Doing a TI-IDF on peribahasa to see what weightage works

peri_csv_clean$Peribahasa_ganda = str_replace_all(peri_csv_clean$Peribahasa, '-', '_')

words_p <- tibble(line = 1:2286, text = peri_csv_clean$Peribahasa_ganda) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text) %>%
  count(line, word)

total_words_p <- words_p %>% 
  group_by(line) %>% 
  summarize(total = sum(n))

words_p <- left_join(words_p, total_words_p)
## Joining, by = "line"
# this is good
words_p %>% bind_tf_idf(word, line, n) %>% group_by(line) %>% top_n(2, wt = tf_idf) %>% anti_join(malaystopwords, by = c("word" = "stopwords")) 
words_p %>% bind_tf_idf(word, line, n) %>% group_by(line) %>% top_n(2, wt = tf_idf) %>% anti_join(malaystopwords, by = c("word" = "stopwords")) %>% arrange(desc(tf_idf))

  1. Peribahasa itu simile?

Apparently there are 4 types of peribahasa: simpulan, bidalan, perumpamaan & pepatah. (ikr Im shooketh) But I think perumpamaan is the type that we normally associate peribahasa with.

They are recognised by the comparitive words like bagai, seperti, laksama.

perumpamaan <- c("bagai", "seperti", "laksama", "umpama", "ibarat", paste0('\\b', 'bak ', '\\b'))

peri_csv_clean %>% 
  mutate(length = str_count(Peribahasa, '\\w+')) %>% 
  mutate(type = if_else(str_detect(Peribahasa, paste(perumpamaan, collapse = "|")), 'Perumpamaan', '')) %>% 
  filter(type == "Perumpamaan") %>% 
  arrange(length)
  1. Nature, binatang, body parts

I took the liberty of accessing the Nouns csv to see what are the common nouns that are used in Peribahasa.

They can be categorised into: Nature-related stuff, binatang, body parts. For example, nature-related stuff would be lautan, padi, langit, ombak. I think it signposts to how we live off the sea at one point coz archipelago eh?

Another research paper says that peribahasa is strongly tied to our person and values. Much of the comparison draws back to orang-related and orang, hati and anak is one of the most frequently occuring nouns.

And of course, binatang. I think its cool that gajah makes the top list coz DO WE HAVE GAJAH IN SINGAPORE? Apparently in Johor have and they have once or twice swam across that causeway to Ubin and Tekong. But also these peribahasa are from all over the Malay land so Malaysia got gajah lah.

Harimau gets featured too! But not Singa.

Spotlight on anjing, ayam and kucing, maybe tikus. Further reading confirms my hypothesis that peribahasa featuring anjing are oftentimes related to deter people from bad values. Does it tie to the Islamisation of Malay people coz anjing najis. (but I love doggos uwu)

I guess another cateogory that I can find is food like nasi, and some other buah2. I like to think of it as a representation of how Malay people used to have dusun at kampong but I think at this point Im over-reaching.

nouns %>% filter(`Col Word` != 'bak' & `Col Word` != 'laksana') %>% head(20)
